<div class="wp-block-image wp-image-60233">
<figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><span class="image-clickable"><img loading="lazy" src="How%20to%20Create%20Notification%20Services%20with%20Redis,%20Websockets,%20and%20Vue_fichiers/vue-message-733x1024.webp" alt="" class="wp-image-26671" sizes="(max-width: 411px) 100vw, 411px" width="411" height="574"></span><figcaption>A Redis message displayed in the view application.</figcaption></figure></div>


<p>As you can see, it is pretty easy to push content to your web 
frontend in real time using WebSocket. So now lets improve the design 
and add a more user-friendly interface using Bootstrap.</p>



<p><strong>Creating an alert block with Bootstrap</strong></p>



<p>In this section, we’ll show you how to use a<a href="https://bootstrap-vue.org/docs/components/alert/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"> Bootstrap alert component</a>, which appears when a new message is received and disappears automatically after a few seconds, using a simple countdown.</p>



<p><strong>Main.js file</strong></p>



<p>Open the main.js file and add the following lines after the last import:</p>



